<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR]]></title><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/most-popular/<atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/theatlantic/most-popular" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[The Atlantic - MOST-POPULAR - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 18 日星期二 06:09:14 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Why the Remote-Work Debate Stays So Heated]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>谈话通常会突出生产力和公司文化等大问题，但员工在哪里工作的问题是非常个人化的。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/C9uTFuz-5brHPsAys00WYgH6Pc8=/0x266:5121x3147/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_862664210/original.jpg" alt="人们在夜间经过一座建筑物" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>彼得·凯德/盖蒂</figcaption></figure><small><i>这是</i>《大西洋<i>日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>在这里注册。</i></a></small><br><br>一个人工作或希望工作的物理空间与他们最个人的选择相交叉。今天，我们将探讨远程工作的争论以及为什么它仍然如此激烈。<br><br>首先，这是<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>的四个新故事：<br><br><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/">商人打破了好莱坞。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/">再见了末日先知。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/mother-having-cancer-treatment-children/674706/">我得了癌症。我不能再把孩子放在第一位了。</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/joe-lieberman-interview-no-labels-2024-election/674711/">乔·利伯曼权衡特朗普的风险。</a></li><strong>在一起更好吗？</strong><br><br> 2021年夏天，我开始回到办公室。吸引我的并不是饮水机闲聊的诱惑，也不是提高生产力的承诺。当时，我只是真的想坐在空调里。那是六月。它是热的。在冰冷的中城大楼里使用办公桌——这与我的客厅相去甚远，在布鲁克林气温高达 90 度的日子里，客厅往往会变得潮湿——似乎是一项重大福利。我与室友住在一起，接种了疫苗，并且没有照顾孩子的职责。每天早上，我都会戴上口罩，在背包里装上几罐咖啡和三明治，以维持一天的生活。当我回到家时，我常常感觉好多了：我发现，当你走进办公室时，很难有一天什么事情都没有发生。<br><br>我想要回到离开家的日常生活的愿望部分是受到我现在的同事艾伦·库欣 (Ellen Cushing) 在 2021 年<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>上发表的一篇<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2021/03/what-pandemic-doing-our-brains/618221/">文章</a>的启发，该文章讲述了流行病的单调对我们的大脑造成的影响。 “有时我会把自己想象成一名模拟市民，当我度过一天时，一个菱形光标悬停在我的头顶上。任务出现了，我就去做。吃饭时间到了，我吃饭。需求出现，我就会满足它们，”她在一篇令人难忘的文章中写道。在另一篇文章中，她引用了一位专家的说法，“环境丰富”——在通勤途中见到新朋友、观察新事物——有利于我们大脑的可塑性。 2021 年 3 月读完这篇文章后，我开始坚信，在通勤途中观察随机的人会让我的思维保持敏锐。<br><br>然后秋天来了，我的更多同事也是如此。很高兴见到他们。有时，中午回到相对僻静的家并在展望公园散步也很棒。我很幸运能够拥有这种灵活性。现在我在<i>《大西洋月刊》</i>工作，我几乎每天都去办公室。我很高兴结识新朋友，并且再次坐在工业级空调中。<br><br>我之所以向你们讲述我的个人经历，是因为对于所有关于生产力、指标和公司文化的讨论，重返办公室的话题都是非常个人化的。由于与我的年龄、经济状况、环境、健康状况和生活方式有关的各种原因，我的需求和愿望可能与那些处于这些轴上其他位置的工人的需求和愿望非常不同。一些在职父母表示，他们可能会看重接送时间的灵活性。一些有色人种员工提出了免受<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://hbr.org/2022/05/research-the-real-time-impact-of-microaggressions">办公室微侵犯</a>的好处。最近的大学毕业生可能想进入办公室交朋友。当然，并非所有员工都能够远程工作。一个人工作或希望工作的物理空间与一个人最个人的选择相交叉。它与人们最看重的东西相碰撞并揭示出来。<br><br>研究远程工作的斯坦福大学经济学教授尼克·布鲁姆告诉我，“研究和证据正在慢慢赶上”在家工作的争论。他预测，五年后，这个话题的争议将会减少。布鲁姆和两位同事何塞·玛丽亚·巴雷罗（Jose Maria Barrero）和史蒂文·J·戴维斯（Steven J. Davis）本月早些时候发表了一份<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://drive.google.com/file/d/1kqbngD8pemqxAkZmWCOQ32Yk6PXK9eVA/view">工作论文</a>，其中收集了一些现有的在家工作研究，其中既有他们自己的工作，也有其他论文。一个有趣的发现是，尽管完全远程工作与生产力下降相关，但混合工作（广泛出现在科技和商业服务等白领领域）与任何生产力损失无关，而且实际上<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://siepr.stanford.edu/publications/working-paper/evolution-working-home">有助于招聘和留住员工</a>。<br><br>过去几年，工人们在工作条件方面获得了自由。现在， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/20/business/return-to-office-remote-work.html">许多老板</a>正试图夺回这种权力。对于重返工作岗位的风险，工人和管理者并不总是意见一致。布鲁姆和他的同事向经理和员工询问在家工作如何影响生产力。总体而言，员工表示，在家工作时，他们的工作效率平均提高了 7.4%；老板们表示，他们认为员工的工作效率降低了 3.5%。经理们往往最欣赏他们眼前所见的东西，布鲁姆在电子邮件中告诉我：“这就像那些厨房开放并展示的餐厅——感觉更像是在享受美妙的烹饪体验，但这实际上只是海市蜃楼。”<br><br>公司要求员工重返工作岗位的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/05/31/business/work-home-return-office-amazon.html">理由</a>似乎很模糊，除此之外，似乎只是在一起会更好（或者，在某些情况下，雇主希望履行昂贵的房地产义务）。支持面对面工作的一个论点是，年轻员工可以向工作场所经验丰富的同事学习并接受指导。布鲁姆告诉我，50 岁以上的高级管理人员在家工作时提供的指导时间与在办公室时一样，大约占 50%。 “很多指导都是随意、轻松的对话，是的，这是自发的——把某人拉到一边并给出一些快速的建议，”他说。皮尤研究中心 3 月份的一项调查发现， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pewresearch.org/short-reads/2023/03/30/about-a-third-of-us-workers-who-can-work-from-home-do-so-all-the-time/">36% 的远程工作人员</a>表示，远程工作损害了他们获得指导的机会。积极的远程指导是可以发生的（我发现主要通过 Zoom 进行的正式指导计划非常有用）。布鲁姆说，虽然从理论上讲，只要有合适的软件，这些类型的关系就可以蓬勃发展，但“实际上，这种情况在网上发生的情况并不多。”<br><br>布鲁姆的观点（以及我对此的反应）强化了个人经历如何影响对这个问题的看法：就我而言，我既享受远离家乡的时光，也相信远程导师关系的潜力。但这些工作维度如何融入我们的生活可能会有很大差异。改变任何输入——个人通勤时间、年龄、工作性质、育儿责任、目标——最终的方法可能会变得无法识别。<br><br><b>相关</b>：<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/03/us-remote-work-impact-fertility-rate-babies/673301/">远程工作的惊人效果</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/01/good-management-mentorship-remote-world/621219/">如何指导偏远世界的年轻工人</a></li><strong>今日新闻</strong><br><br><li>俄罗斯正在停止<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/17/world/europe/ukraine-russia-grain-deal.html">黑海粮食倡议</a>，该倡议确保乌克兰可以在战时封锁的情况下通过海运出口粮食，并有助于稳定全球粮食价格。</li><li>参议员乔·曼钦 (Joe Manchin) 决定与无标签组织 (No Labels) 共同举办一场活动，这<a href="https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-senator-manchin-speech-stokes-speculation-white-house-run-2023-07-17/">引发了人们对第三方潜在总统竞选的猜测</a>。</li><li>消防队员正在<a href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/16/us/california-wildfires-extreme-heat/index.html">扑灭南加州的几场野火</a>，这些野火是在高温警告下于本周末引发的。</li><b>晚读</b><br><br>帮自己一个忙，去寻找“第三个地方”<br><br><em>作者：艾莉·康蒂</em><br><br><p>去年的一个周日，我在下午早些时候的冥想课上结束回家途中，步行穿过宾夕法尼亚州的一个郊区。其中一栋不起眼的灰泥房子的邮箱上贴着一张奇怪的贴纸，上面写着“麦克俱乐部”。我检查了谷歌地图，看看自己是否站在一家巧妙伪装的企业旁边——在城市里可能被自命不凡地称为地下酒吧——但什么也没有出现，所以我偷看了房子里面。就在那里，我发现了一张台球桌，一个中年男子坐在长长的桃花心木吧台的尽头，独自喝着血腥玛丽。显然我偶然发现了一个为附近居民开设的社交俱乐部。尽管一开始调酒师对我刚刚走进来感到难以置信，但他很快就奖励了我一杯吉尼斯黑啤酒来奖励我的冒险精神。那天老鹰队没有参加 NFL 比赛，他很感激有额外的陪伴。我们谈论了即将到来的鹿季节，在得知我是一名新猎人后，两个人向我展示了一把放在另一个房间的步枪。 ……</p><p>除了给我一种收缩了萎缩肌肉的感觉之外，这种互动对我来说很特别，因为我在郊区找到了一个经典的“第三个地方”，这是我最意想不到的地方。该术语由社会学家雷·奥尔登堡 (Ray Oldenburg) 在 20 世纪 80 年代创造，本质上是指工作或家庭以外的物理位置，在那里几乎没有或没有经济障碍，并​​且对话是主要活动。</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/04/third-places-meet-new-people-pandemic/629468/">阅读全文。</a><br><br><b>更多来自<em>大西洋月刊</em></b><br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/alabama-execution-jimi-barber/674708/">伊丽莎白·布鲁尼格：阿拉巴马州想杀死吉米·巴伯。</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-kennedy-covid-anti-semitism/674727/">RFK Jr. 反犹太主义最令人震惊的方面</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/dominos-deliver-uber-eats-app/674716/">送货应用程序完成了不可能的任务。</a></li><b>文化突破</b><br><br><b>读。</b>英国诗人帕特里克·麦基的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/mozart-in-motion-his-work-and-his-world-in-pieces-patrick-mackie/9780374606206?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>《动感的莫扎特》</i></a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/mozart-in-motion-book-review-music/674726/">探索了莫扎特持久魅力的秘密</a>。<br><br><b>手表。</b>在狂欢和淫荡的背后，节目<i>《戴夫》</i> （在 Hulu 上播出）构建了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/dave-fx-tv-show-male-friendship/674719/">一个不太可能的男性友谊模型</a>。<br><br><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/free-daily-crossword-puzzle/">玩我们的日常填字游戏。</a><br><br><strong>聚苯乙烯</strong><br><br>我喜欢烘焙，觉得这样做很放松。但到了夏天，当我的公寓很热时，我就会转向不需要烘烤的食物。 （如果还没有弄清楚：我不喜欢过热的感觉。）我回到的一个非常简单和有趣的杯子是这些<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://cooking.nytimes.com/recipes/1018460-chocolate-peanut-butter-cups">巧克力花生酱杯</a>，由 Samantha Seneviratne 提供。我没有双层锅炉或微波炉，所以我在平底锅中煮水，然后在上面的金属碗中融化巧克力片。我喜欢腰果酱，所以我用腰果酱代替花生酱。努力与回报的比率很高：只需几分钟的积极工作，就能带来令人愉快的小享受。<br><br> — 洛拉<br><br><i>Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 22:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/remote-work-return-to-office-policies/674736/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/remote-work-return-to-office-policies/674736/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Businessmen Broke Hollywood]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>现在他们不想支付员工工资。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/0uua5U8CtPMn05n96loBLb7ojPs=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/hollywood_strike/original.jpg" alt="好莱坞演员罢工的照片。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大卫·布托 / Redux</figcaption></figure>好莱坞机器——从剧本写作、拍摄和制作，到深夜脱口秀公关——已经正式停止运转。<br><br>周四， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/sag-aftra-national-board-votes-approve-strike/story?id=101210303#:~:text=More%20than%20160%2C000%20members%20of,to%20hit%20the%20picket%20lines.">演员们举行罢工。</a>在无所畏惧的情景喜剧保姆弗兰·德雷舍 (Fran Drescher) 的领导下，SAG-AFTRA 的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/US/sag-aftra-national-board-votes-approve-strike/story?id=101210303#:~:text=More%20than%20160%2C000%20members%20of,to%20hit%20the%20picket%20lines.">16 万名成员</a>在与制片厂的谈判破裂后停止了工作。他们加入了美国作家协会的行列，该协会的成员（包括我本人）自五月以来一直在罢工。<br><br>自 1960 年以来，我们两个工会就没有一起罢工过。拍摄地点的编剧纠察队已经关闭了估计 80% 的制作。现在，美国演员工会的罢工规则规定，演员不仅不能为作品拍摄或做配音工作，而且还不能为作品拍摄或配音。他们也不能参加红地毯或宣传任何电影协会的项目——这已经是一个挑战，因为编剧罢工已经关闭了作为新闻界主要内容的夜间脱口秀节目。<br><br>就像编剧一样，演员们也在寻求增加剩余报酬——类似于版税支票的补偿——曾经可靠的收入在转向流媒体的过程中几乎消失了。演员们也在利用他们的声音和图像寻求针对人工智能的保护。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/writers-guild-of-america-strike-residuals-pay-streaming/673876/">霍奇特尔·冈萨雷斯：“一切都从我们开始”</a><br><br>迪士尼首席执行​​官鲍勃·艾格 (Bob Iger) 称这些期望“不现实”。他指责罢工者“增加了该行业已经面临的一系列挑战，坦率地说，这些挑战非常具有破坏性和危险性。”<br><br>就在几天前，一位工作室高管告诉<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/07/writers-strike-hollywood-studios-deal-fight-wga-actors-1235434335/"><i>Deadline</i></a> ，他们的策略是“让事情拖延下去，直到工会成员开始失去他们的公寓和房子”。<br><br>驱逐是一种相当残酷的劳资谈判策略。<br><br>好莱坞的首席执行官们<i>正在</i>遭受苦难。主要不是来自劳资纠纷、行业混乱或公共关系问题，而是来自明显的无知，这似乎是所有行业高管的普遍现象。在向华尔街交付的压力下，太多的首席执行官失去了自己电影的情节。他们经营公司并不是为了盈利地提供优质产品，例如一本书或一杯咖啡，或者在这种情况下，是一部电影或电视节目。他们经营公司是为了创造丰厚的利润。他们的产品质量已经不再重要。<br><br>如果你对此表示怀疑，请考虑一下上周宣布艾美奖提名时，最大的份额流向了 HBO Max，这个享有盛誉的平台已<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.insiderintelligence.com/content/charting-new-course-adapting-advertising-landscape-after-hbo-max-discovery-merger">不复存在</a>，因为华纳兄弟探索频道 (Warner Bros. Discovery) 拿走了这个传统品牌的流媒体部门，并将其合并到一个充斥着低预算真人秀节目的凌乱应用程序中。我们处于颠倒的状态。<br><br>作家和演员都陷入了流媒体的转向，其疯狂的逻辑<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://variety.com/2023/tv/news/writers-guild-contract-negotiation-mini-room-1235568173/">颠覆了长期的工作实践</a>，慢慢开始用<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2019/5/28/18637135/hollywood-ai-film-decision-script-analysis-data-machine-learning">人工智能</a>取代人类本能，并消除了工人的收入来源。<br><br>例如，演员马克·普罗克什 (Mark Proksch) 在<i>《办公室》</i>中客串一季的剩余收入中赚了更多钱，<i> </i>在旧体制下，比他在新体制下主演<i>《我们在阴影中做什么》</i>五季还要多<i>。</i><br><br>现在，正当好莱坞工作人员认为我们需要调整薪酬模式以适应流媒体时代时，制片厂却告诉我们，我们无法获得公平的报酬，因为流媒体模式已被打破。正是那些打破了这一规则的工作室高管——其中许多是<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://deadline.com/2023/05/ceo-pay-wga-writers-strike-1235351572/">千万富翁</a>——告诉了我们这一点。<br><br>这是最高管理层无知的另一个方面：疯狂的高管薪酬让领导者完全脱离了他们雇用的员工的生活。华纳兄弟和探索频道的首席执行官大卫·扎斯拉夫 (David Zaslav) 2021 年收入为 2.47 亿美元，这一事实让人很难接受他拒绝在每年导致中产阶级演员损失数千美元的问题上做出让步的事实。<br><br>你可以随心所欲地争论是否有人应该赚这么多钱，但这些领导者做出了一些灾难性的商业决策。<br><br>在大流行期间每个人都被困在家里的短暂时刻，转向流媒体是非常有利可图的。人们不能在音乐会、外出就餐或旅行上花钱，因此他们在流媒体服务上花费异常金额感到放心。<br><br>好莱坞的首席执行官看到了 Netflix 的成功，竞相复制一种模式，但不知道这种模式是否可持续，这种模式依赖于工会人才不断生产新的（且昂贵的）娱乐内容。他们对企业的看法是错误的，但更错误的是他们认为劳工会遵守规定。这个支点不是演员和编剧做出的，而是演员和编剧做出的。他们为什么要付出代价？<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/05/hollywood-writers-strike-wga/673926/">阅读：为什么你应该关注好莱坞编剧的罢工</a><br><br>如果转向流媒体是一个错误，导致这些企业真的陷入困境——考虑到这些高管薪酬方案的规模，这种情况很难成立——我们也将不得不受苦。但如果我们在困难时期受苦，我们也应该在富裕时期分享利润。这就是谈判的目的。高管们能够纠正这艘船的唯一方法就是重新制作不容错过的节目，如果没有我们，他们将无法做到这一点。<br><br>由于缺乏优秀的剧本作家，好莱坞的高管们只能借鉴玛丽·安托瓦内特的台词。但革命者已经在外面拆除了宫殿。在伦敦，<i>奥本海默</i>的演员们<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cbsnews.com/news/oppenheimer-stars-walk-out-london-premiere-actors-strike-emily-blunt-matt-damon-florence-pugh-cillian-murphy/">走出了</a>电影的首映式。<i>芭比娃娃</i>的新闻发布会已停止；就连明星们粉红色的社交媒体账户也被黑了。艾美奖颁奖典礼可能会被<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/06/21/business/media/emmy-awards-writers-strike.html">推迟</a>。动漫展将没有演员或作家。我非常希望电影公司能够早日认识到，即使这会暂时伤害股东，但从长远来看，好的娱乐永远是好生意。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 19:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/hollywoods-cruel-strategy/674730/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[A Voicebot Just Left Me Speechless]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>生成式人工智能解决了困扰我的语音助手多年的问题。<br>说出我的名字 Saahil Desai 并不难。 Saahil：与<em>锯木厂</em>押韵，或者至少可以让你达到 90%。 Desai：就像<em>决定</em>把最后一点砍掉。确实如此。<br><br>然而，我的名字常常会被淹没在一大堆失态和错误中。最常见的一个，Sa <em>-heel</em> ，至少是一个诚实的尝试——不像它的突变双胞胎，一个单音节的混乱，听起来像<em>海豹。</em>其他人则违背了所有可能的逻辑。有一次，一位大学同学读到我的名字，停顿了一下，然后自信地说：“嗨，西雅图。”<br><br>但最让我烦恼的错误发音却不是任何人都能说出来的。它们来自机器人。一整天，Siri 都会通过塞在我耳朵里的 AirPods 读出我的短信，并将我的名字混入<em>Sahul</em>中。它比我用来转录采访的人工智能服务要好，后者通过一串似乎从失败的英国男孩乐队中剥离出来的名字（奈杰尔、萨尔、迈克尔、丹尼尔、斯科特·希尔）来识别我。硅谷渴望其产品能够改变世界，但显然这也意味着名称的改变<em>。</em><br><br>或者至少我是这么认为的。听听这个： <br><br><iframe allow="autoplay" class="lazyload" data-src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/1567406875&amp;color=%23ff5500&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;show_teaser=true&amp;visual=true" frameborder="no" height="100" scrolling="no" title="嵌入互动内容" width="100%" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe> <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="萨希尔·德赛">Saahil Desai</a> · <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503/eleven-labs" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="十一个实验室">Eleven Labs</a>这是来自 ElevenLabs 的一个名为 Adam 的人工智能声音，ElevenLabs 是一家专门从事语音克隆的初创公司。 （这有点像音频中的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2022/09/ai-art-generators-future/671568/">DALL-E</a> 。）这个机器人不仅能很好地说出我的名字，而且还能很好地说出我的名字。它比我能更好地说出我的名字。毕竟，萨希尔来自梵语，而我不会说这种语言。最终的结果是一种熟悉的多巴胺的冲击，一种令人惊奇的感觉，就像在技术上找到一个刻有你名字的纪念品钥匙链一样。<br><br>除了可以写俳句的聊天机器人和可以按照毕加索风格绘制披萨的艺术机器人之外，生成式人工智能革命还催生了最终可以确定我的名字的语音机器人。正如 ChatGPT 从互联网帖子中学习到的那样，ElevenLabs 在大量音频片段上训练其声音，以了解如何像人们一样说话——至少<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://beta.elevenlabs.io/blog/the_first_ai_that_can_laugh/">500,000 小时</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://beta.elevenlabs.io/blog/the_first_ai_that_can_laugh/">，而</a>早期语音模型需要<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://research.facebook.com/file/649409006862002/paper_fixed.pdf">数十或数百</a>小时的音频。 “我们在过去两年里一直在开发一种新的语音基础模型，”ElevenLabs 首席执行官 Mati Staniszewski 在一封电子邮件中写道。 “这意味着我们的模型是上下文感知且与语言无关的，因此能够更好地捕捉名称等细微差别，并提供反映文本输入的语调和情感。”较新的语音机器人的数据可能包括任意数量的专门用于<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.howtopronounce.com/">发音的</a>网站，如果有人在有声读物、播客或 YouTube 视频中正确说出了你的名字，较新的人工智能模型可能会记录下来。<br><br>亚马逊、谷歌、Meta 和微软等公司也在开发更先进的语音机器人——尽管它们仍然是鱼龙混杂。我在他们每个人的人工智能语音程序上测试了同一句话——“来吧，说 Saahil Desai 并不难”。他们都能应付德赛，但迎接我的却不是萨希尔完美发音的合唱。亚马逊的 Polly 软件可能比 Siri 更糟糕，它认为我的名字类似于 Saaaaal： <br><br><iframe allow="autoplay" class="lazyload" data-src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/1567407838&amp;color=%23ff5500&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;show_teaser=true&amp;visual=true" frameborder="no" height="100" scrolling="no" title="嵌入互动内容" width="100%" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe> <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="萨希尔·德赛">Saahil Desai</a> · <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503/amazon-polly" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="亚马逊波莉">Amazon Polly</a>谷歌云和 Microsoft Azure 都无伤大雅，但并不完美，稍微将 Saahil 扭曲成一种明显陌生的东西。没有什么可以打败 ElevenLabs，但 Voicebox（Meta 尚未发布的工具）非常接近：该公司<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ai.facebook.com/blog/voicebox-generative-ai-model-speech/">最近将其吹捧</a>为“语音生成人工智能的突破”： <br><br><iframe allow="autoplay" class="lazyload" data-src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/1567408888&amp;color=%23ff5500&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false&amp;show_teaser=true&amp;visual=true" frameborder="no" height="100" scrolling="no" title="嵌入互动内容" width="100%" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe> <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="萨希尔·德赛">Saahil Desai</a> · <a href="https://soundcloud.com/saahil-desai-968221503/meta-voicebox" style="color: #cccccc; text-decoration: none;" target="_blank" title="元语音盒">Meta Voicebox</a>计算机现在可以说出比我自己的名字更多的名字。加州大学伯克利分校计算机科学家 Hany Farid 在一封电子邮件中写道：“前几天，我和我的学生在 CNN 安德森·库珀的 ElevenLabs 上录制了一段录音，内容是‘Hany Farid 教授完全就是个彻底的笨蛋’（这是一个很长的故事），我也注意到了同样的事情。” “我很惊讶它能很好地发音我的名字。我还注意到它可以正确发音我的非美国学生的名字。”我测试过的其他棘手的名字也表现良好：ElevenLabs 确定了 Lupita Nyong&#39;o 和 Timothée Chalamet，尽管它把可怜的 Pete Buttigieg 的姓氏变成了非常不幸的 Buttygig。<br><br>人工智能声音现在可以说出不寻常的名字，这可不是一件小事。他们面临着同样的发音困难，这让许多人感到困惑。像 Giannis Antetokounmpo 这样的名字不遵守英语规则，而即使是一个更简单的名字也可以有多种发音（And <em>rea</em>或<em>And</em> rea？）或拼写（Michaela？ Mikayla？ Mikayla？ Michela？）。 Farid 表示，如果 AI 声音的颜色和纹理听起来比人类的 HAL 9000 更高，那么这个名字可能仍然听起来平淡无奇。<br><br>前几代语音助手——Siri、Alexa、Google Assistant、汽车的 GPS——只是没有足够的信息来完成所有这些步骤。 （在某些情况下，你可以自己提供这些信息：Apple 的一位发言人告诉我，你可以在通讯录应用程序中手动输入姓名的拼音，以调整 Siri 的读取方式。）法里德写道，多年来，这项技术“确实处于停滞状态”。 “它真的很难穿过那个恐怖谷，它有点像人类，但也有点奇怪。然后它就直接冲破了门。”受人脑启发的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/2106.15561.pdf">“深度学习”技术的</a>进步可以更容易地发现音高、节奏和语调的模式。<br><br>这就是人工智能目前的奇怪矛盾：尽管这项技术很容易产生偏见，从而疏远用户（语音助手比白人说话者<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://academic.oup.com/applij/advance-article/doi/10.1093/applin/amac066/6901317">更容易错误地识别</a>黑人说话者的话语），但它也可以帮助消除冒泡的较小的疏远感。不断听到机器人错误地说出我的名字是一种数字侮辱，它提醒我，我的设备似乎不是为我而设计的，尽管 Saahil Desai 在印度是一个常见的名字。我的蓝色 iPhone 12 是一块六英寸厚的平板，它比我生命中的任何其他物品都更能容纳<em>我</em>。然而它仍然搞砸了我身份的最基本的事情。<br><br>但机器人能够理解并说出我和你的名字的世界也是一个令人毛骨悚然的世界。 ElevenLabs 所采用的声音克隆技术已被用来制作可信的深度伪造品——粗鲁的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/03/ai-taylor-swift-fan-generated-deepfakes-misinformation/673596/">泰勒·斯威夫特</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/03/politicians-ai-generated-voice-fake-clips/673270/">乔·罗根和本·夏皮罗辩论</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/03/politicians-ai-generated-voice-fake-clips/673270/"><em>《料理鼠王》</em></a> 、艾玛·沃特森阅读<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/1/31/23579289/ai-voice-clone-deepfake-abuse-4chan-elevenlabs"><em>《我的奋斗》</em></a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/1/31/23579289/ai-voice-clone-deepfake-abuse-4chan-elevenlabs">的一部分</a><em>。</em>当另一端的声音可以像你的亲戚一样说出你的名字时，冒充你认识的人的人工智能骗局就更加可信。<br><br>一旦我清楚地知道我无法击败 ElevenLabs，我就输入了我的中间名 Abhijit。出来的是一团乱七八糟的音节，我永远也骗不了。好吧，好吧：我承认说萨希尔·阿比吉特·德赛实际上很难。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 16:41:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ai-voice-assistants-name-pronunciation/674731/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/ai-voice-assistants-name-pronunciation/674731/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Alabama Wants to Kill Jimi Barber]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>经过一年的拙劣处决之后，国家急于证明它可以平安无事地杀人。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/UrwkBtH4ugOeKubFNhkUDy-Ntac=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/JimiBarber-3/original.png" alt="吉米·巴伯和死囚图像的插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>保罗·斯佩拉/《大西洋月刊》插图。资料来源：ADOC；盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>去年，阿拉巴马州的死刑室连续三起处决<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/08/joe-nathan-james-execution-alabama/671127/">失败</a>，创造了历史。两名被判死刑的人在被处决后幸存下来： <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/10/alabama-inmate-execution-alan-miller/671620/">艾伦·米勒</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/11/alabama-death-penalty-kenneth-smith-execution/672220/">肯尼思·史密斯</a>。两人都被反复用针刺穿，试图设置静脉注射线，直到他们的死刑令午夜到期，迫使刽子手停止进一步杀害他们的企图。<br><br>鉴于这场危机，州长凯·艾维 (Kay Ivey) 下令从 11 月开始暂时暂停执行死刑，并宣布“对该州的执行过程进行自上而下的审查”，以便“该州能够成功地伸张正义。”<br><br>艾维在发给记者的电子邮件声明中说：“为了受害者及其家人的利益，我们必须把这件事做好。”艾维在 2 月 24 日致阿拉巴马州总检察长史蒂夫·马歇尔 (Steve Marshall) 的一封信中取消了暂停执行，指示他再次寻求该州死囚牢房的死刑执行日期。尚未发布有关审查结果的公开报告。<br><br>尽管如此，这项审查的结果将在即将于 7 月 20 日执行的詹姆斯·“吉米”·巴伯 (James “Jimi” Barber) 的处决中得到检验。巴伯因 2001 年谋杀阿拉巴马州祖母多萝西·埃普斯 (Dorothy Epps) 而被定罪，他在喝得酩酊大醉时用锤子将她打死。三天后，阿拉巴马州将再次尝试注射死刑，这是自最近一系列失败以来的首次注射死刑——这一次还有一系列额外的要求：证明该州惩教部实际上能够成功执行死刑；向州总检察长办公室提供该证据，以便在正在进行和未来的诉讼中使用；正如艾维州长所说，为了受害者及其家人的利益，一切顺利地完成。该州实现这一目标的可能性仍不清楚。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/11/alabama-death-penalty-kenneth-smith-execution/672220/">伊丽莎白·布鲁尼格：暴力史</a><br><br>到目前为止，阿拉巴马州的官员还没有证明自己能够对刽子手的技能做出负责任的判断。检验国家审查结果和改善努力效果的方法，就是尝试处决另一个人。巴伯是这个实验的不幸对象。<br><br>艾维的“自上而下的审查”从一开始就不够充分。今年2月7日，在短暂的暂停期间，170多名阿拉巴马州宗教领袖签署了一封致艾维的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://apnews.com/article/alabama-state-government-tennessee-kay-ivey-religion-930f4c2015e763afced960dcc2e999f4">公开信</a>，表示希望审查能够采取合法形式：“我们与统一战线进行对话，要求对阿拉巴马州的执行协议和程序进行独立、外部、全面的审查，就像其他有类似问题的州所做的那样。”接下来的内容没有回答这些描述符。艾维没有像<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2014/04/30/308372080/oklahoma-governor-calls-for-independent-review-of-botched-execution">2014 年</a>俄克拉荷马州州长玛丽·法林和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tn.gov/governor/news/2022/5/2/gov--lee-calls-for-independent-review-following-smith-reprieve.html">2022 年</a>田纳西州州长比尔·李那样任命一个独立委员会来调查惩教部处理处决的情况并发布报告，而是指示该机构进行自我审查并向她公布调查结果。美国商务部于 2 月 24 日提交了报告，距离神职人员信函劝告艾维进行第三方审查仅几周，也是艾维宣布暂停实施的大约三个月后。<br><br>阿拉巴马州惩教署署长乔恩·哈姆在一封信中通知艾维办公室，审查已经结束。他写道：“该部门对我们的处决程序进行了深入审查，”包括评估该部门处理囚犯最后上诉的法律策略、参与处决的工作人员和医务人员的培训程序、该部门执行处决所使用的医务人员数量、如何最好地协助医务人员执行处决，以及支持该州紧张的杀戮计划所需的设备。哈姆说，卫生部已经增加了医疗人员队伍，进行了额外的排练，并购买了新设备，为恢复职责做准备。他在信中用了很多篇幅赞扬艾维。<br><br>阿拉巴马州程序中最重大的变化与该州刽子手执行任务的时间有关。<br><br> “根据你的要求，”哈姆写道，“阿拉巴马州最高法院改变了安排处决的规则。”他提到了 2022 年 12 月艾维致该州九位最高法官的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.al.com/news/2022/12/gov-kay-ivey-asks-alabama-supreme-court-to-change-rule-on-setting-execution-dates.html">一封信</a>，要求他们修改一项特定规则，以便法院不再签发 24 小时死刑令（具有具有法律约束力的午夜到期时间），而是允许艾维本人设定一个可以跨越任意天数的执行时间框架。鉴于阿拉巴马州曾两次因刽子手未能在指定执行日期午夜之前设定两条静脉注射线而不得不取消执行死刑，仅这项修正案（法院于今年<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/news/2023/01/13/al-supreme-court-gives-governor-power-to-set-timeframe-for-executions/69805360007/">1 月</a>批准艾维）就为一个更为严重的问题提供了权宜之计。当艾维设定今年 5 月处决巴伯的时间框架时，她授权该州刽子手在 7 月 20 日午夜至 7 月 21 日凌晨 6 点之间的任何时间杀死巴伯。该程序原定于 20 日下午 6 点开始，而法院的改变意味着刽子手们现在有至少 12 个小时来接触巴伯的静脉，而不是六个小时。简单来说，这创造了一种可能性，即一个完全清醒的巴伯可能被绑在死刑犯身上。在行刑台上呆了半天，而州刽子手则在他的身体上探查合适的静脉。<br><br>执行阿拉巴马州囚犯的医务人员的身份、资格和培训受到国家的精心保护。但巴伯正在进行的诉讼中，一些细节已经变得清晰起来，该诉讼寻求氮气缺氧，这是阿拉巴马州另一种合法可用的处决方法，而不是注射死刑。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/12/alabama-botched-executions-2022-gas/672607/">氮气缺氧</a>是一种从未尝试过的气体处决方法，尽管目前还没有概述其安全使用的协议，但在法律上仍然是该州死囚的一种选择。<br><br>在本月早些时候的一次听证会上，巴伯的律师透露，阿拉巴马州新静脉注射团队的专业执照包括两名护理人员、一名高级急救人员和一名于 2019 年在佛罗里达州获得多州执照的注册护士。在上月初提交的诉状中，巴伯的律师告诉阿拉巴马州中区的一名法官，他们相信他们可能已经发现了该静脉注射团队一名成员的身份，并发现此人因欺诈和相关民事判决而多次被捕反对他或她。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/12/alabama-botched-executions-2022-gas/672607/">伊丽莎白·布鲁尼格：阿拉巴马州计划用毒气杀死囚犯</a><br><br>至于哈姆所说的阿拉巴马州为实现行刑流程现代化而大肆吹嘘的新设备：该州在六月份告诉巴伯的律师，它所添加的只是“用于将囚犯固定在行刑轮床上的额外带子”。<br><br>如果阿拉巴马州的努力成功，巴伯只是第一个；很快就会有更多的处决。阿拉巴马州目前正陷入有关肯尼思·史密斯的诉讼中，但去年秋天未能执行死刑。本月，史密斯的诉讼在该州的驳回动议中幸存下来，使阿拉巴马州危险地接近发现阶段的边缘。很快，除非有什么变化，否则它可能不得不向史密斯的律师交出有关其执行程序和人员的信息——该州一直在拼命避免这种情况，并且在州政府未能杀死艾伦·米勒后​​，在他的诉讼中与他达成和解，从而成功地避免了这种情况。在今年二月提交的强制证据开示动议中，史密斯的律师警告说，一旦美国商务部的审查结束，“我们预计被告将采取行动，为史密斯先生设定另一个处决日期，并在史密斯先生有机会证据开示之前有效地提起诉讼”，杀死史密斯。巴伯的成功处决可能有助于该州支持恢复处决，包括史密斯的处决。<br><br>与此同时，巴伯很平静。 “我的精神状态很好，”他最近写信给我。 “神对我是如此信实和仁慈！ ……担心是恐惧的一种形式，而我们没有那种精神！只有爱、欢乐、和平和理智。恐惧是对不存在的事物的不切实际的担忧。不怕。如果那一刻到来，上帝的应许就将属于我！没有恐惧或恐惧，莉兹小姐。只是对我的主表示虔诚的敬畏。”<br><br> Barber&#39;s execution, like all of the other past and future executions in Alabama, would be, in Ivey&#39;s telling, for the victims and their families—though in Barber&#39;s case, at least one member of his victim&#39;s family <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/james-barber-alabama-death-row-forgiveness/674181/">has forgiven him</a> , and isn&#39;t looking forward to his execution. Barber and Sarah Gregory, his victim&#39;s granddaughter, connected via letter in 2020, and have developed a friendship since. Yet victims&#39; family members who do not wish to see prisoners executed don&#39;t seem to be who the governor has in mind; the botched execution of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/08/joe-nathan-james-execution-alabama/671127/">Joe Nathan James</a> in July of 2022 also happened against the express and vocal wishes of his victim&#39;s family. Whatever desire is actually driving Alabama&#39;s zealous pursuit of judicial killings, it seems related to the wishes of grieving families only theoretically, not specifically.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 14:31:07 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/alabama-execution-jimi-barber/674708/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/alabama-execution-jimi-barber/674708/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[I Have Cancer. I Can’t Put My Kids First Anymore.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> How will my two children survive this assault on my motherhood, on my capacity to care for them? <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/qur6QzoAVl_0o0pIwGscgsqF_10=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/cancer_motherhood_holly_stapleton/original.jpg" alt="woman in bathtub" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Holly Stapleton for The Atlantic</figcaption></figure><small>这篇文章发表在《今日必读的一个故事》中，这是一份时事通讯，我们的编辑在其中推荐了《大西洋月刊<i data-stringify-type="italic">》周一至周五</i><i data-stringify-type="italic">必读的一篇文章</i>。 <i data-stringify-type="italic"><a data-event-element="inline link" data-sk="tooltip_parent" data-stringify-link="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" delay="150" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/one-story-to-read-today/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">在这里注册。</a></i></small><br><br> In February, two months before my 40th birthday, my left breast became swollen and painful. I chalked it up to the catchall pile of indignities known as perimenopause. But March and April came and went, and my breast seemed worse. May arrived, and I scrambled to schedule a mammogram. I feared the worst, but a mammogram proved harder to come by than I&#39;d imagined. When I finally secured an appointment, I brought my sister because I was so certain that something was very wrong.<br><br> It turned out, crushingly, that my worry had not been prophylactic. The radiologist was nervous and somber; she told us that she was “very concerned” by the mass in my breast and my lymph nodes, but that the hospital couldn&#39;t offer me a biopsy for weeks. Basically, I had cancer, but no one could tell me anything more about it. Patting my arm as if I were a recalcitrant dog, she sent me to a nurse practitioner down the hall who tried to pick up the pieces of my life.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/05/mothers-day-afghanistan-kabul/674045/">Read: The lesson I wish I never had to learn about motherhood</a><br><br> “I can&#39;t wait two weeks for a biopsy,” I told her, weeping. “I&#39;ll go anywhere, anytime.”<br><br> She had been officious, reassuring, distracted by her keyboard, but she stopped and looked up at me then.<br><br> “That&#39;s helpful. A lot of mothers say they can&#39;t do a certain day, or time, because of their kids&#39; soccer or something.”<br><br> I couldn&#39;t tell whether she judged me for my indifference toward my children&#39;s extracurriculars, or whether she judged those other mothers. <i>I</i> judged them. As a social worker who supports children and their caregivers, I had spent years droning on to adults about the value of a predictable routine in a child&#39;s life, but really: What did it matter if those kids got to soccer practice if their mother was dead?<br><br> “Their father will drive them to dance class,” my sister told the nurse crisply. “We need a biopsy.”<br><br> She said she would see what she could do.<br><br> My sister and I left the hospital, stunned to have my worst fears confirmed, but knowing next to nothing of a diagnosis or prognosis. The radiologist and the nurse practitioner and their mammogram machines were in a fancy Boston suburb, and we had to walk past a Kumon tutoring enterprise to get to an expensive coffee shop. We sat outside, where a young person accompanied by two older people talked loudly and ceaselessly about her impending graduation from a very prestigious local university. The older people couldn&#39;t get a word in edgewise. My sister and I eavesdropped, muted by our own grief. I thought again and again of the mothers driving to practice or tournaments or Kumon, their cancers blossoming within them, unchecked, while they sliced oranges, hauled lacrosse sticks, loaded math apps onto the iPad, and cheered themselves hoarse.<br><br> I was itchy with the horror of knowing I had cancer but knowing nothing more, and with the horror of all of these women putting off their mammograms or their biopsies or even their physicals because they were busy being taxis for the children they hoped to drop off in 10 years at the prestigious university. The college student loudly clarified her position on a topic of no interest to me.<br><br> But even as I raged, my children swelled to fill my mind. My eldest is 10—leggy and knowing, but still transfixed by Calico Critters—and her younger brother is 5: goofy, round-cheeked, lisping, sweetly solicitous, and still undecided on whether fairies are real or not. The thought of them existing without my care—without a mother to order their school uniforms, or to talk them off the ledge of heartache, or to bandage their wounds, or to read <i>Charlotte&#39;s Web</i> aloud before bed and weep with them at Charlotte&#39;s beautiful demise—was unbearable and all-consuming. Their vulnerability was all I could think about; it shoved out my own pain, my fears for my body and for my life.<br><br> In the following weeks, I secured a biopsy, an oncologist, and finally a diagnosis and a plan: The cancer is aggressive, but it has not spread to vital organs or bones. The tumor will likely be responsive to treatment. My children will probably keep me, but first I must endure trial by fire for a year: chemotherapy, a mastectomy, daily radiation, and regular drug therapy.<br><br> My life has crumbled around me; my husband&#39;s brow has formed a permanent furrow. Two years ago, I had surgery; he took the children away in the immediate aftermath so that I could sit in a quiet house with my father, my sole tasks to eat and sleep and heal. We both know that he will give me the same space, or try to, over the coming months. But I will have to accept it, again and again.<br><br> I began treatment in early June. And, in short order, I began to feel terrible.<br><br> Chemotherapy poisons the cancer, and it poisons the body: the membranes of the mouth and nose, the stomach lining, your bone marrow and joints. I spend a lot of time in my bed. My two children visit me and jump on said bed. Sometimes I indulge this. Sometimes I suggest that they go away. I long to feel less vile, with a yearning stronger than I have ever known: It is stronger than lust or the desire to protect my babies.<br><br> Providence, where I live, is a small town; it turns out that my daughter&#39;s friend&#39;s mother&#39;s partner practices acupuncture and specializes in helping people undergoing chemotherapy. I made an appointment; the only time available was during my daughter&#39;s piano lesson. I dropped her off, and then realized that the acupuncture office is downstairs from her music school. I lay on the table as the acupuncturist went about his tasks, and it took me a long time to notice that the fitful piano music was coming not from the small Bluetooth speaker on the counter next to me, but from upstairs. <i>Was that my daughter playing?</i> I didn&#39;t think so, but I couldn&#39;t be sure; I didn&#39;t always pay rapt attention to her practicing at home. I had missed her recital the previous weekend, sickened by chemo.<br><br> For acupuncture to “work,” you have to “relax.” I was not relaxed. I wondered the following: <i>Is it Lola playing above me? Had she been</i> very <i>sad that I missed the recital?</i> <i>A friend of mine and her daughter had gone, and had brought Lola a bouquet of pale pink ranunculus; this had assuaged my guilt, but what had it meant to her?</i> <i>Is my daughter thinking of me now, as she plays? Is she worrying about me? Is her worry capable of seeping through the ceiling, like a leak? How will my two children survive this assault on my motherhood, on my capacity to care for them? How will they survive my inability to provide them with predictable days and evenings?</i> The music above me became consuming: I had to know if it was my familiar girl playing.<br><br> I ran my fingers along the edge of the pale-green sheet that covered my body. It was hard not to think of a shroud or a morgue covering. It was impossible not to think of my daughter.<br><br> Just before I started chemo, my friend Margaret came by and sat on my blue couch. She told me a story—a cautionary tale—from two years prior, when she had been undergoing treatment for ovarian cancer. She was in a chemo slump, but there was a basket of clean laundry in her bedroom, and it looked at her insistently—it was a symbol of caretaking and mothering and a household that needed attention—so she shoved her fatigue aside and folded the damn laundry. Finishing the single basket took her hours, after which she was demolished by the effort and had to take a nap. “It wasn&#39;t worth it,” she told me. “But I thought it was.”<br><br> I listened with horror, and repeated the story to my husband, whose brow furrowed deeper with worry. He was taking it all in—we were both coming to understand that I would not be good for much in the coming months. Friends and relatives offered to come and help, and though we might have once demurred, we said, <i>Yes, please, thank you so much, what day will you arrive, how long can you stay?</i><br><br> “Who will do … all the things you do?” one friend asked me as I explained the treatment plan.<br><br> “I don&#39;t know,” I said. “But it won&#39;t be me.” But as I said it, I knew that I would keep hearing the siren song of the laundry basket, of my daughter&#39;s playing. And that I would have to cover my ears.<br><br> Each day has brought new reminders of my own fragility, all that I am losing or will soon lose—my hair, my productivity, a breast, bodily integrity, reproductive function, faith that my body is an ally rather than an enemy, the capacity to enjoy flavorful foods and tend to my children without risk to myself. I imagine Margaret&#39;s basket of clean laundry, and I imagine letting it sit, unfolded.<br><br> Sometimes the children appear to kiss me goodnight fresh from their shower, or to relay some good news, and I feel like a distant mother in an English period piece. Except that I am not busily ordering frocks from London or tending to my correspondence on thick cream-colored stationery; I am lying inert, watching yet another man murder yet another woman on <i>Happy Valley</i> . In those moments, I wonder who I am.<br><br> The creation and maintenance of stability, safety, and routine for my children have been the prayer beads of my adult life. The idea that any upheaval in my own life—a move, a death, a pandemic—affects them as well as me has been an organizing principle of not just my parenting, but my survival. It has kept me moving forward when times are hard.<br><br> It&#39;s hard to abandon the idea of curating my children&#39;s experience of my cancer, to close the door to my bedroom against the cacophony of bedtime, to give in to the primacy of my own needs and simply rest. Enduring treatment and healing have become my goals, superseding the idea that my most important task is to parent in the best or most optimal way. Retreating into myself, away from my kids, feels like an unlearning of everything I have been taught as a mother, or have imparted to others, but I cannot see another way to survive.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/04/motherhood-children-it-goes-so-fast-book/673649/">Mary Louise Kelly: The hardest decisions mothers make</a><br><br> At my second acupuncture appointment, I lay on the table and managed to focus on my breath; I slipped in and out of sleep.<br><br> My children&#39;s experience of this catastrophe—this wrenching, miserable time—will leave its mark on their small psyches. But my task right now, I realized, is to swim through fire. They will wait, watching, on the shore. The acupuncturist quietly entered the room to move the needles around, to shift my limbs up or down. He said nothing as he did this, and I, too, was silent, perhaps afraid to break a spell. <i>I will blow them kisses from the river</i> , I think. <i>Someone else will need to stand with them on the water&#39;s edge, holding their hands.</i><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 11:32:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/mother-having-cancer-treatment-children/674706/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/mother-having-cancer-treatment-children/674706/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Joe Lieberman Weighs the Trump Risk]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The No Labels co-chair says a third-party ticket won&#39;t help Trump in 2024. Democrats are dubious. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/cg84lZt1ywrOgleA7CPlzmryEI4=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/joe_lieberman/original.jpg" alt="乔·利伯曼" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Christopher Goodney / Bloomberg / Getty</figcaption></figure> Joe Lieberman wants to make one thing clear. “The last thing I&#39;d ever want to be part of,” the former Connecticut senator and onetime vice-presidential nominee told me by phone last week, “is bringing Donald Trump back to the Oval Office.”<br><br> Democrats have their doubts. Lieberman and his former party have been warring for years, ever since he won a fourth Senate term, in 2006, as an independent after Connecticut Democrats dumped him in a primary. Suddenly liberated, Lieberman endorsed the Republican John McCain over Barack Obama in 2008 and proceeded to tank the Democrats&#39; dreams of enacting a public health-insurance program through the Affordable Care Act.<br><br> He&#39;s now a co-chair of No Labels, the centrist group that, to the growing alarm of Democrats, is preparing to field a third-party presidential ticket in 2024. The organization&#39;s leaders say they&#39;re trying to save voters from a binary rematch between Trump and President Joe Biden that most Americans <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/2023/04/25/2024-trump-biden-presidential-rematch">have told pollsters</a> they don&#39;t want. But Democrats and more than a few Republicans fear that such a plan might ensure exactly what Lieberman insists he would hate to see: Trump&#39;s return to the White House. Both No Labels&#39; own polling and independent surveys <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.axios.com/2023/07/12/no-labels-poll-third-party-manchin">have shown</a> that a “moderate, independent” candidate could capture as much as 20 percent of the popular vote and would pull more of that support from Biden than from Trump. If the 2024 election is as close as 2020&#39;s—and pretty much every political prognosticator believes it will be—that could be decisive.<br><br> No Labels has already lost one of its co-founders, William Galston, over its push for a third-party ticket; Galston <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/no-labels-may-re-elect-donald-trump-third-party-independent-galston-rematch-f2e7697d">resigned in protest</a> this spring over the possibility that the bid could tip the election to Trump. Democratic members of the No Labels–backed Problem Solvers Caucus in the House have disavowed the effort for the same reason. The moderate Democratic group Third Way is adamantly opposed to the idea, and a new bipartisan group <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2023/07/11/gephardt-no-labels-third-party/">is forming</a> to stop it.<br><br> For now, Lieberman is undeterred. “I think people in both parties, particularly the Democrats, are greatly overreacting,” Lieberman told me. “They really would do better to try to build up support for their own ticket and adopt a platform that&#39;s more to the center.”<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/proportional-representation-house-congress/674627/">Read: A radical idea for fixing polarization</a><br><br> Founded by the Democratic fundraiser Nancy Jacobson, No Labels launched in 2010 with an initial focus on promoting centrist policies and breaking partisan gridlock in Congress during the Obama presidency. It formed the Problem Solvers Caucus in 2017 and has touted some of the major bipartisan bills that have passed with Biden&#39;s support, including the 2021 infrastructure law. It is now putting significant money behind an idea—a so-called unity ticket featuring one Democrat and one Republican—that has <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.politico.com/story/2007/02/unity08-plans-to-field-fusion-ticket-aimed-at-moderates-002657">come up</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2019/01/17/bipartisan-presidential-unity-ticket-heal-divided-america-2020-column/2583404002/">repeatedly</a> over the past two decades but never actually materialized. Leaders of No Labels have said they won&#39;t decide whether to nominate a ticket until the spring, when they would assess the major-party nominees and see what polling shows about the effect a third-party bid might have. So far they&#39;ve refused to discuss who their actual candidates might be.<br><br> Citing <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://roar-assets-auto.rbl.ms/files/52325/HarrisX%20No%20Labels%20-%20Insurance%20Policy%20Data%20-%2030%20March%202023%20-%20VF.pdf">a large poll</a> the group commissioned in December, No Labels has argued that a third-party ticket could win enough states—including some that are deeply red and deeply blue—to capture the Electoral College. Lieberman acknowledged that that remains a tall order. He said No Labels wanted a potential unity ticket to play “a constructive role” even if it didn&#39;t win, drawing both parties back toward the ideological middle. They are hoping, for example, that one of the two parties will embrace the “Common Sense” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.commonsensemajority.org/_files/ugd/9f0726_a8092681d4cc40ae8623b98b83d3853d.pdf">policy agenda</a> it released yesterday. It&#39;s not clear, however, that this would make Biden or Trump any more palatable to voters.<br><br> The group&#39;s lodestar is the late Ross Perot, who captured 19 percent of the vote in 1992 and was the last third-party candidate to draw significant popular support. Lieberman credits Perot&#39;s bid for prompting President Bill Clinton to embrace policies that led to a balanced federal budget; many Republicans believe the Texas businessman cost George HW Bush a second term. More recent third-party candidates such as Jill Stein in 2016 have garnered much less support but played more obvious spoiler roles, delivering Republican presidential victories. And Lieberman, who was Al Gore&#39;s running mate in 2000, is well aware of the impact that Ralph Nader had in that election, when he took crucial votes away from the Democratic ticket in Florida.<br><br> “When I look at the data next year, I&#39;m going to be very cautious about interpreting it,” Lieberman said. “If it appears that, notwithstanding our goals, we may create a real risk of inadvertently helping to reelect Donald Trump, I will be strongly opposed to running a third-party ticket. And I think I&#39;m reflecting a majority of people in No Labels, including the leadership.”<br><br> For all of Lieberman&#39;s talk about caution, however, the group is aggressively laying the groundwork for what it calls a national “insurance policy” against a Biden-Trump rematch. No Labels is pursuing a $70 million effort to secure ballot access in every state and has already made progress in a few important battlegrounds. Today, Senator Joe Manchin of West Virginia and former Utah Governor Jon Huntsman will headline the formal launch of the group&#39;s “Common Sense” agenda in New Hampshire. Manchin has not ruled out running for president on a No Labels ticket, although he <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/mkraju/status/1679178567756791808">insisted to CNN</a> that his high-profile visit to the early-primary state was no indication that he&#39;s warming to the idea.<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2021/11/how-moderates-could-actually-take-control-washington/620599/">Matthew Yglesias and Steven M. Teles: A moderate proposal</a><br><br> Lieberman is clear about his distaste for Trump, but he&#39;s hazier on the question of why—or even whether—Biden has fallen short. He&#39;s said repeatedly that if the choice came down to Biden or Trump, he&#39;d vote for the Democrat, and he speaks affectionately of a man he first met nearly 40 years ago and with whom he served for 20 years in the Senate. Yet he&#39;s still hunting for a better option. I asked him whether he supported a third-party ticket because Biden had done a bad job or because voters <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://projects.fivethirtyeight.com/biden-approval-rating/">think</a> he&#39;s done a bad job. “I think it&#39;s both,” Lieberman replied. “He&#39;s an honorable person, but he&#39;s been pulled off his normal track too often” by pressure from the left. That&#39;s a frequent talking point from Republicans and a complaint Manchin has made from time to time.<br><br> The perception that Biden has veered too far to the left, though, is not what <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2021/12/democrats-biden-approval-rating/621048/">has driven</a> his <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/broad-doubts-bidens-age-acuity-spell-republican-opportunity/story?id=99109308#:~:text=President%20Joe%20Biden's%20job%20approval,in%20early%20preferences%20for%202024.">low approval ratings</a> . Indeed, in many ways Biden is the kind of president for whom moderates like Lieberman have long been clamoring. Yes, he signed two major bills that passed along purely party-line votes (the American Rescue Plan Act in 2021 and the Inflation Reduction Act a year later), but he has repeatedly prioritized negotiating with Republicans, most recently <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/05/biden-gop-debt-ceiling-negotiation/674070/">over the debt ceiling</a> . Lieberman credited Biden for his bipartisan infrastructure law and the budget deal he struck with House Speaker Kevin McCarthy this spring. “He&#39;s done some significant things,” Lieberman said, also praising the president&#39;s initial handling of the coronavirus pandemic. When I asked him what specifically Biden had veered too far left on, he initially declined to list any issues. Then he pointed to No Labels&#39; policy plan, noting that it included “commonsense” proposals on guns and immigration.<br><br> Although he&#39;s been out of office for more than a decade, Lieberman, at 81, is less than a year older than Biden. He said he believes the president remains up to the job, both physically and cognitively, and he was reluctant to call on him to stand down. But Lieberman gently suggested that might have been the better course. “I&#39;m struck by how intent he is on running again,” he said with a chuckle. “It would have been easier for him not to run, and he could retire with a real sense of pride and just an enormously productive career in public service.”<br><br> Lieberman&#39;s response subtly pointed to No Labels&#39; hope that, come springtime, their decision will be an easy one. Perhaps Biden will change his mind and withdraw, or Trump&#39;s legal woes will finally persuade Republican voters to look elsewhere. At the moment, neither of those scenarios seems likely.<br><br> Lieberman and his allies might decide that nominating a third-party ticket won&#39;t help reelect Trump, but that&#39;s not something they can know for sure. I asked Lieberman: If he was so intent on keeping Trump out of office, wasn&#39;t that too big a risk to take? He didn&#39;t have a clear answer. “Yeah,” he replied. “I mean, we&#39;ll see.”<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 11:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/joe-lieberman-interview-no-labels-2024-election/674711/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2023/07/joe-lieberman-interview-no-labels-2024-election/674711/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[An Unlikely Model for Male Friendship]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Beneath the hijinks and lewdness, the show <em>Dave</em> charts how real vulnerability is essential to male bonding. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/eX98TEiP7hMw4Gw40ESacalsFuA=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/dave_bromance/original.jpg" alt="Two men sit on the ground in conversation in a scene from &quot;Dave.&quot;" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> ByronCohen / FX</figcaption></figure> The last memory I have of a certain former friendship, one of singular intimacy and closeness, involves watching an episode of the FXX show <em>Dave</em> . It was two summers ago, and a few of us had gathered for his birthday. As the night waned, slices of cake crumbling and cans of beer warming, we watched the show. We guffawed and recognized bits of ourselves in the group of strivers who were all trying, in some form, to <em>make it</em> . At the time, I was ignorant of the fact that my friendship would end abruptly the next day. But in the aftermath of that breakup, as I attempted to cope with the pain, I was surprised by how much <em>Dave</em> would also illuminate my notions of friendship—and its complications.<br><br> <em>Dave</em> is a loosely autobiographical show about Dave Burd, aka Lil Dicky, a white rapper who in real life has had modest success: In 2016, he was featured in <em>XXL</em> magazine&#39;s influential “Freshman Issue” alongside Lil Yachty, 21 Savage, Anderson .Paak, and Lil Uzi Vert, among others. The show is also, more absurdly, one that focuses on Lil Dicky&#39;s small, deformed penis (the result of a rare birth defect and several surgeries), which the artist fully embraces both inside and outside the series for body positivity as well as schtick. (Just consider his moniker.) Assembled in the show around Dave are friends who have been absorbed by his ambition to become a global star. Imagine combining Larry David&#39;s neurosis with Kanye West&#39;s hubris with a lighthearted genitalia fixation and you might conjure a decent approximation of the protagonist.<br><br> Much like <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2022/03/atlanta-season-3-review/629394/"><em>Atlanta</em></a> , <em>Dave</em> is hilarious, moody, artfully shot, and a commentary on contemporary American hip-hop culture. Many rappers and celebrities appear as themselves to comedic effect, and the series cleverly pokes fun at the obvious perils of a white dude seeking fame through a Black art form. But look past the hijinks and the studio sessions thick with smoke, bravado, and dick jokes, and <em>Dave</em> is fundamentally a show about male friendship that complicates the typically reductive on-screen bromance. It has some of the most raw depictions of male bonding on TV today, illustrating how race, culture, and ambition can both define—and confine—how men relate to one another. Even more important, the show attempts to convey how real vulnerability might be the best hope we have of transcending those barriers.<br><br> Early in Season 1, we meet Mike, Dave&#39;s ginger-headed roommate and close friend who becomes his manager. The two are touchingly familiar—it isn&#39;t unusual for them to part with unironic <em>I love you</em> ’s or bathe together, with Mike trying out various ointments to cure the acne on Dave&#39;s back. The scene that sets up the latter ritual takes place in a supermarket aisle with another character, the frenetic GaTa (pronounced like <em>gator</em> ), Dave&#39;s newest friend in LA and eventual hype man. Mike sidles up to them with a basket of new oils to try in the tub, expressing such earnest excitement that I found myself awaiting a punch line. But there wasn&#39;t one, and I was left to check my reflexive reaction to what platonic male intimacy could look like.<br><br> At this point, <em>Dave</em> ’s core friend group—and its unique dynamic—is taking shape. Elz, Dave&#39;s wry producer and childhood best friend, played by Travis Bennett (aka Yung Taco from the rap group Odd Future), is soon added to the fold. Each character is allowed to be unique in his own way: absurd, misguided, extreme. Though race certainly inflects these relationships—Elz and GaTa are Black; Dave and Mike are white—the group is so raucous and tender that occasional tensions seldom disrupt their closeness.<br><br> Neither do profoundly personal issues. For instance, later in Season 1, at a rehearsal for an upcoming concert, GaTa&#39;s energy is visibly off. Dave, Mike, and Elz can see that he&#39;s pacing and overly agitated, but are frustrated about his seeming lack of preparedness. GaTa eventually sits on the couch and confesses that he&#39;s bipolar. He has a “chemical imbalance,” he admits, through tears, and he takes eight to 10 pills a night to cope. Moved by GaTa&#39;s vulnerability, the group rallies around him, and clearly begins to understand the intricate engine that powers their friend. The show thrums with this kind of collective revelation followed by understanding. Every time it occurs, the bonds among the four thicken further. Rewatching this episode, I thought of my former friend, and how hard it is to know what someone is going through or how much of it they&#39;ve chosen to share. In order for a relationship to sustain itself and grow, curiosity must search out new things to know—and to love.<br><br> In a time of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/01/loneliness-solitude-pandemic-habit/672631/">deep alienation, estrangement, and loneliness</a> , such portrayals of male companionship are refreshing. For a long while, the bromances I most saw on-screen were in buddy-cop films such as the <em>Bad Boys</em> and <em>Lethal Weapon</em> franchises, where affection is earned after displays of strength or courage. Even newer and earnestly affectionate comedies such as <em>I Love You, Man</em> don&#39;t focus as squarely as <em>Dave</em> does on how beautiful the romance of male friendship can be. On the show, effusive intimacy isn&#39;t something reached after a villain has been defeated or a romantic conflict overcome, but is terrain worthy of exploration in itself.<br><br><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2022/06/six-ways-make-maintain-friends/661232/">Read: The six forces that fuel friendship</a><br><br> Yet as male intimacy appears more and more in pop culture, so, too, does the complicated nature of its rupture. Hua Hsu&#39;s potent memoir, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/stay-true-a-memoir-hua-hsu/9780385547772?affiliate_id=atl-347"><em>Stay True</em></a> (which, full disclosure, I designed the cover for), is a forensic reconstruction of a close friendship from college, written decades after a tragedy. Martin McDonagh&#39;s darkly funny film <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2022/10/banshees-of-inisherin-2022-movie-review/671801/"><em>The Banshees of Inisherin</em></a> depicts the swift falling out between two old friends in a small Irish town, and the ways they struggle to cope.<br><br> <em>Dave</em> also contends artfully with separations between men—and plots one way to heal them. Friendships that grow from childhood can become complicated in adulthood, and this is embodied by the relationship of Elz and Dave, who have been thick as thieves from the age of 6. In one of Season 2&#39;s standout episodes, Dave is paid a large fee to perform at a bar mitzvah in LA He and Elz have been sniping at each other—Elz is exhausted by Dave&#39;s monomania, and Dave is jealous of Elz&#39;s success working for more established rappers.<br><br> The animosity between them builds slowly, culminating in a game of one-on-one basketball as the bar mitzvah is being set up, their antagonism expressed in a series of quick cuts. The pair best each other with jump shots and drives; jabbed elbows, sweat, and grunts. They&#39;re working out what language has failed to, physically sublimating their pain, which, unsurprisingly, proves an inadequate way to resolve conflict. Their predicament, the show suggests, is a result of the two having lost their ability to communicate openly. Still, by the episode&#39;s end, when the party&#39;s host boots Dave for the terrible influence he&#39;s been on his son, Elz and Dave remember their antics at bar mitzvahs as kids, and summon the less-egoistic joy of their youthful transgressions. In an act of playful defiance, they open the gate penning in a herd of farm animals hired for entertainment and set them free.<br><br> This is typical of how conflicts between friends resolve on <em>Dave</em> : with a reminder that individual pride isn&#39;t worth threatening their bonds. Season 3, which ended in May, is more preoccupied with traditional romance, as each character navigates dating, falling in love, and sex, though their friendships still evolve. But in the penultimate episode, a documentary of Lil Dicky&#39;s tour is screened for the characters, featuring candid testimonials about Dave from his friends. The confessions are biting and loving in equal measure, and I found myself asking what my friends would say if they ever had such a chance. I wondered, in particular, what the friend I lost might offer.<br><br> Naturally, I played a role in the end of our friendship, but not knowing exactly <em>how</em> is a constant torment. We had no one-on-one game through which to try to work things out, let alone a joint moment of vulnerable frustration. The reason we&#39;d watched <em>Dave</em> that summer night was because I&#39;d insisted there were certain scenes he would appreciate; many references that used the lingua franca of our group. And I was right. I remember the satisfaction of his laughter. In hindsight, I wish it had prompted him to say whatever had been on his mind. I wish I&#39;d been curious enough to ask before it was too late.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 17 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/dave-fx-tv-show-male-friendship/674719/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/dave-fx-tv-show-male-friendship/674719/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[The Most Shocking Aspect of RFK Jr.’s Anti-Semitism]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>令人惊讶的不是肯尼迪提出了反犹太阴谋，而是花了这么长时间。 <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/rxpGHPhlsK812tEHTXc5twzmss8=/0x0:2000x1125/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/rfk_illo_horz/original.jpg" alt="小罗伯特·RFK" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：杰米·麦卡锡/盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>上周，在曼哈顿的一次晚宴上，民主党初选候选人小罗伯特·F·肯尼迪分享了他对冠状病毒本质的直率想法。 “有一种观点认为它是针对种族的，”他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nypost.com/2023/07/15/rfk-jr-says-covid-was-ethnically-targeted-to-spare-jews/">在视频中的</a>言论中解释道。 “COVID-19 的目标是攻击白人和黑人。 The people who are most immune are Ashkenazi Jews and Chinese.”肯尼迪补充道，可以肯定的是，“我们不知道它是否是故意针对的。”换句话说，肯尼迪显然认为，这场大流行病是否是由一个阴暗的阴谋集团为了拯救中国和犹太人而策划的，这是一个悬而未决的问题。<br><br>中国至少有 100 万人<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2023/02/china-million-covid-deaths-communist-party/673177/">死于</a>COVID-19；纽约等地的犹太人非但没有对这种病毒免疫，反而常常被<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://bklyner.com/editorial-stop-blaming-orthodox-jews-blame-trump-for-brooklyn-covid-spikes/">不公平地指责</a>为传播病毒的罪魁祸首。作为一名曾与冠状病毒作斗争的犹太人，肯尼迪的说法对我来说是新闻。但考虑到消息来源，他们也并不感到意外。这是因为肯尼迪是一个阴谋论者，而阴谋的弧线很短，并且向犹太人倾斜。<br><br>以下只是肯尼迪<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-jr-2024-election-anti-establishment-voters/674588/">观点</a>的一小部分：无线互联网的辐射<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D3OkKer7Ohw">会导致</a>癌症；供水中的化学物质正在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnn.com/2023/07/13/politics/robert-kennedy-jr-chemicals-water-children-frogs/index.html">造成性别不安</a>；中央情报局杀害了他的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.tabletmag.com/sections/arts-letters/articles/robert-f-kennedy-jr-interview-david-samuels#:~:text=he%20was%20also%20a%20CIA%20asset">父亲</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/3993563-robert-kennedy-jr-sees-overwhelming-evidence-cia-involved-in-jfk-assassination/">叔叔</a>约翰·F·肯尼迪总统；抗抑郁药<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.businessinsider.com/robert-kennedy-jr-elon-musk-american-revolution-twitter-spaces-conversation-2023-6">导致了</a>今天的大规模枪击事件；乔治·W·布什 (George W. Bush) <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://clevelandmagazine.com/in-the-cle/politics/articles/robert-f-kennedy-jr-nut-job">窃取了</a>2004 年总统选举的胜利；你手机的 5G 连接是“收集我们的数据并控制我们的行为” <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://nypost.com/2022/01/23/rfk-jr-compares-pandemic-mandates-to-nazi-germany/">阴谋的一部分</a>。<br><br>从肯尼迪的职业生涯来看，令人惊讶的不是他涉足反犹太主义，而是他花了这么长时间才到达这里。正如我<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/elon-musk-george-soros-anti-semites/674072/">之前写过的</a>：<br><br><p>反犹太主义可以说是世界上<a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/01/texas-synagogue-anti-semitism-conspiracy-theory/621286/">最古老、最持久的</a>阴谋论。它将犹太人描绘成世界政治、经济和社会问题背后幕后操纵的傀儡师。对于那些寻求简单解决生活复杂问题的人来说，这种观点提供了现成的解释——也是敌人。任何寻求社会苦难单一来源的人可能会从普通的阴谋论开始，但很快就会以人云亦云的反犹太思想告终。</p>因为反犹太主义已经产生了几个世纪以来将人类问题归咎于犹太人的材料，所以一个相信有一只看不见的手在操纵世界事务的人最终会发现它属于一个看不见的犹太人。<br><br>因此，在阴谋论边缘流通而不遭遇反犹太主义是不可能的。这就是为什么肯尼迪经常发现自己与那些相信并表达反犹太思想的人在一起。上周，他<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/RobertKennedyJr/status/1678528085258301440">大肆宣传</a>自己与说唱歌手艾斯·库珀(Ice Cube)的会面，艾斯·库珀是一位阴谋论者， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.billboard.com/music/rb-hip-hop/ice-cube-criticized-anti-semitic-images-conspiracy-theories-9400472/">长期以来</a>一直发表奇怪的反犹太主义推文和歌词。过去，肯尼迪还与仇恨传教士路易斯·法拉罕（Louis Farrakhan）达成了<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/LouisFarrakhan/status/614862836431392769">共同</a><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.c-span.org/video/?c4910041/user-clip-rfk-jr-told-louis-farrakhan-cdc-kill-black-boys">目标</a>，后者经常谴责所谓的犹太人控制媒体和政府。<br><br>肯尼迪最终会回应他的阴谋集团的反犹太主义假设是不可避免的。事实上，他远非第一个走上从阴谋主义到彻底反犹太主义这条老路的人。近年来， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://newsletters.theatlantic.com/deep-shtetl/61897999d581bf0020f74c32/why-rep-marjorie-taylor-greene-just-championed-louis-farrakhan/">马乔里·泰勒·格林</a>、 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2022/11/why-its-become-harder-to-joke-about-anti-semitism/672120/">凯里·欧文</a>和<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/05/elon-musk-george-soros-anti-semites/674072/">埃隆·马斯克</a>等形形色色的人已经从普通的阴谋论发展到反犹太论点。就连肯尼迪的 COVID-19 猜想的内容也不是原创的：几个世纪以来，犹太人一直被指责传播瘟疫，最著名的是欧洲<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/the-black-death">黑死病</a>期间。<br><br>周末，肯尼迪在推特上愤怒地否认和澄清， <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://twitter.com/RobertKennedyJr/status/1680227322509635595">坚称</a>他的意思只是说新冠病毒“作为针对种族的生物武器的一种概念证明”，而不是“种族效应是故意设计的”，尽管他在最初的言论中明确提出了这种可能性。<br><br>肯尼迪本人没有反犹太主义历史，也从未表现出对犹太人的个人偏见。但他的阴谋罗盘确保了他最终会到达这个目的地，因为它只指向一个方向。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 17:36:04 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-kennedy-covid-anti-semitism/674727/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/rfk-kennedy-covid-anti-semitism/674727/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Goodbye to the Prophets of Doom]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>关于全球经济的传统观点是富人越来越富，穷人越来越穷。如果事实并非如此怎么办？ <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/AAP-a5AsFwsWVsmF4hkep4tT-TU=/0x0:4800x2700/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/inequality_2/original.jpg" alt="一张美元钞票被折皱得像楼梯的插图" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>大西洋月刊插图。资料来源：盖蒂。</figcaption></figure>在大衰退<span class="smallcaps">期间</span>，公众对经济的讨论经历了极大的失望。<br><br>在这个国家的大部分历史中，大多数美国人都认为未来会给他们或他们的后代带来更大的富裕。尽管经济危机时有发生，但总的情况似乎是每个阶层的人都在进步。这些期望在很大程度上得到了证实：例如，在 20 世纪中叶的大部分时间里，美国工薪阶层所享有的生活水平远远高于一两代人之前的富裕美国人所享有的生活水平。<br><br>但2008年金融危机之后，一段时期的严重经济困难以及经济学家对不平等话题的新兴趣颠覆了这些假设。经济衰退的预测占据了话题。美国这个长期以来以其根深蒂固的乐观主义而闻名的国家，开始对未来感到恐惧——现在看来，大多数人拥有的东西会越来越少。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/inflation-jobs-unemployment-recession/674593/">Adam Ozimek：差点引发经济衰退的简单错误</a><br><br>三个论点为“大失望”提供了思想基础。第一个由麻省理工学院经济学家戴维·奥托提出的颇具影响力的观点是，大多数美国人的工资在人们的记忆中第一次出现停滞。尽管在上个世纪的大部分时间里，美国人的平均收入大约每代人翻一番，但大多数人的工资增长在 20 世纪 80 年代开始趋于平稳。到 2010 年，较贫穷的美国人似乎面临着一个生活水平不再能得到任何真正改善的未来。<br><br>第二个论点与全球化对全球收入分配的影响有关。在一张后来被称为“大象曲线”的图表中，塞尔维亚裔美国经济学家布兰科·米兰诺维奇认为，世界上最贫穷的人只经历了很小的收入增长；中间百分位数从全球化中受益匪浅；那些中上层阶级——包括美国等富裕国家的许多产业工人和服务业人员——的收入停滞不前；最富有的人像强盗一样亲热。全球化似乎是一件喜忧参半的事情，而且对于美国等工业化经济体的底层工薪阶层来说，这显然是一件令人担忧的事情。<br><br>最后也是最全面的争论是关于不平等的性质和原因。尽管大部分人口刚刚维持繁荣，但最富有的美国人的财富和收入却在迅速增长。法国经济学家托马斯·皮凯蒂在 2013 年出人意料的畅销书<i>《二十一世纪的资本》</i>中提出，这种趋势可能会持续下去。皮凯蒂认为，资本的回报早已超过了劳动力的回报，他似乎暗示，只有像一场重大战争这样的灾难性事件——或者似乎不会出现的激进的政治变革——才能帮助遏制日益加剧的不平等趋势。<br><br>巨大的失望继续影响着许多美国人对当前和未来经济状况的看法。但随着大流行和通货膨胀的上升改变了世界经济，这篇论文的知识基础已经开始动摇。经济悲观主义的理由开始看起来不再像以前那样令人信服。是时候修改“大失望”的核心原则了吗？<br><br>作为美国最著名的劳动经济学家<span class="smallcaps">之一</span>，奥托尔在过去十年中提供了有关美国工人收入停滞的大量证据，特别是对于那些没有大学学位的工人。<br><br>奥特尔在 2010 年一篇极具影响力的<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.hamiltonproject.org/publication/policy-proposal/the-polarization-of-job-opportunities-in-the-u-s-labor-market-implications-for-employment-and-earnings/">论文</a>中写道，美国经济正在出现分化。尽管对高技能工人的需求上升，但对“中等工资、中等技能的白领和蓝领工作”的需求却在萎缩。美国经济曾经提供了大量的中产阶级就业机会，现在正分裂为一个非常富裕的专业阶层和一个变得更加贫困的剩余阶层。奥托尔表示，总体结果是“非大学工人的实际收入下降”和“工资不平等急剧加剧”。<br><br>奥托过去对美国劳动力主要部分工资下降的研究使他现在听起来更加乐观，这一点更加值得注意。奥托在今年早些时候发表的一份<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://economics.mit.edu/sites/default/files/2023-03/The%20Unexpected%20Compression%20-%20Competition%20at%20Work%20in%20the%20Low%20Wage%20Labor%20Market.pdf">工作论文</a>中指出，由于公司在疫情末期拼命寻找工人，低薪工人发现自己处于更好的讨价还价地位。经济命运发生了显着逆转。<br><br> “分布底部不成比例的工资增长降低了大学工资溢价，并将自 1980 年以来总体工资不平等的上升趋势扭转了约四分之一，”奥托尔写道。近期经济趋势的大赢家正是那些在过去几十年中被排除在外的群体：“40岁以下且没有大学学位的工人的工资上涨尤其强劲。”<br><br>奥托尔表示，即使考虑到通货膨胀因素，美国底层四分之一工人的收入多年来首次出现显着增长。这位之前曾写过美国劳动力“两极分化”的学者现在得出的结论是，美国经济正在经历“意外的压缩”。换句话说，贫富差距正在以惊人的速度缩小。<br><br>一位<span class="smallcaps">作家并不是</span>唯一一位对大失望的基础产生怀疑的主要经济学家。米拉诺维奇认为，他的“大象曲线”之所以如此有影响力，部分原因是它证实了许多人对全球化影响的担忧。 <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.socialeurope.eu/global-income-inequality-time-to-revise-the-elephant">他现在承认</a>，他著名的图表是“对许多人想法的实证证实”。他对那条传统智慧不再那么确定了。<br><br>几年前，米兰诺维奇开始更新最初的大象曲线，该曲线基于 1988 年至 2008 年的数据。结果令人震惊——一个积极的结果。一旦 Milanovic 将下一个十年的数据纳入到 2018 年，曲线的形状就发生了变化。这条曲线的病毒性名称不再是“上升、下降、再上升”的特征，而是稳步下降的梯度现在似乎描绘了一幅简单且乐观得多的图景。在他现在调查的四十年里，世界上最贫穷的人的收入增长得非常快，中间分布的人的收入增长得相当快，而最富有的人的收入则相当缓慢。几乎每个人的全球经济状况都在改善，而且与传统观点相反，获得最大回报的是最贫困的人，而不是最富裕的人。<br><br>在<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.foreignaffairs.com/world/great-convergence-equality-branko-milanovic"><i>《外交事务》</i>最近发表的一篇文章</a>中，米兰诺维奇走得更远。 “我们经常被告知，”他写道，“我们生活在一个不平等的时代。”但当你查看最新的全球数据时，你会发现这是错误的：事实上，“世界正变得比 100 多年来更加平等。”<br><br><span class="smallcaps">直到今天</span>，皮凯蒂仍然是大失望的守护神。没有哪个思想家比他更频繁地被援引来证明这一理论的合理性。但即便是皮凯蒂十年前做出的悲观诊断，现在看起来也没有那么可怕了。<br><br>部分原因是皮凯蒂的研究受到了其他经济学家的批评。根据一种有影响力的论点，皮凯蒂错误地理解了为什么二战后几十年里许多工业化国家的资本回报率高于劳动力回报率。皮凯蒂认为，如果没有一致的压力来阻止这种情况发生，资本主义的本质将永远有利于亿万富翁和大公司，而不是普通工人。但根据西北大学经济学家马修·罗尼利 (Matthew Rognlie) 的说法，皮凯蒂对此的解释<i> </i>在此期间，不平等现象的加剧是由于对数据的误解。<br><br>罗格利认为，20 世纪下半叶资本回报率过高的主要原因是巴黎和纽约等大都市中心房价的大幅上涨。如果这一时期的资本回报率高于劳动回报率，那么原因不是一般的经济趋势，而是特定的政治因素，例如限制性的建筑规范。此外，主要的受益者并不是皮凯蒂所关注的亿万富翁和大企业，而是他们的利益。相反，他们是中上层专业人士，拥有大城市的大部分住房。<br><br>经济学家们仍在争论这些批评是否切中要害。但就在皮凯蒂为自己的工作辩护的同时，他本人也开始对经济的长期结构表现出更加乐观的态度。在他 2022 年出版的著作<i>《平等简史》</i>中，他将不平等的加剧视为一种异常现象。 “至少自十八世纪末以来，出现了一场争取平等的历史性运动，”他写道。 “2020 年代的世界，无论看起来多么不公正，都比 1950 年或 1900 年的世界更加平等，而后者本身在许多方面都比 1850 年或 1780 年的世界更加平等。”<br><br>与奥托尔和米拉诺维奇一样，皮凯蒂似乎也得出结论，“大失望”的论点在关键方面是错误的。<br><br>现在就消除对收入停滞或不平等加剧的担忧<span class="smallcaps">还为时过早</span>。三位前末日预言家都强调社会和政治因素在塑造经济结果中所发挥的作用。因此，他们认为最近较贫穷的美国人的工资增长部分是由唐纳德·特朗普和乔·拜登为应对这一流行病而推行的扩张性经济政策造成的。<br><br>同样，世界上一些最贫困人口近几十年来所取得的巨大成就部分归功于其政府利用产业政策来塑造全球化对其国家影响的努力。正如皮凯蒂所说，从长远来看，资本回报是否会超过劳动力回报，取决于有关税收和再分配、工会实力和劳动力市场规则的政治决策。<br><br> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/06/labor-shortage-low-unemployment-inflation/674263/">奥伦·卡斯：劳动力短缺的神话</a><br><br>最近关于我们经济前景的好消息不应让我们得出可能很快就会变得过于乐观的结论。但我们也应该避免使本能的悲观主义持续下去，这种悲观主义看起来越来越没有根据。尽管悲观主义可能看起来很聪明或精明，但对我们建设更美好世界的集体能力的愤世嫉俗只会让我们更难为创造未来所需的经济政策赢得支持。<br><br>进步主义者有时似乎相信，他们可以通过让未来看起来可怕来动员人们。但当选民感到受到威胁时，通常是不择手段的反动派做出不切实际的承诺，并把受益的局外人当作替罪羊。工资停滞和不平等加剧仍然是我们必须保持警惕的真正危险，但更美好的经济未来看起来更容易实现这一事实应该值得大肆庆祝。<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/economics-inequality-piketty-milanovic/674702/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[A Canceled Comedy Gem]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Entertainment musts from Alan Taylor <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/BHOk5GUq5x1xS0XjNNT8BVyz-I0=/0x0:4217x2372/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/TCDJOPE_EC004_1/original.jpg" alt="Joe Pera waving" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> John Nowak / Adult Swin / Everett</figcaption></figure><small><i>这是</i>《大西洋<i>日报》的一个版本，是一份时事通讯，可引导您了解当天最大的故事，帮助您发现新想法，并推荐最好的文化。</i> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/sign-up/atlantic-daily/"><i>在这里注册。</i></a></small><br><br> Welcome back to The Daily&#39;s Sunday culture edition, in which one <i>Atlantic</i> writer reveals what&#39;s keeping them entertained. Today&#39;s special guest is our photo editor, Alan Taylor, who has published <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/03/our-photo-editors-must-see-images/673521/">more than 2,000 photo articles</a> during his time at <i>The Atlantic</i> .<i> </i>Alan recently compiled images of humans and animals <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/07/photos-keeping-cool-during-heat-waves/674606/">keeping cool during heat waves</a> , and some photos of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/07/photos-shark-ocean-beach/674623/">the wondrous lives of sharks</a> .<br><br> Alan is hoping that another platform picks up the canceled<b> </b><i>Joe Pera Talks With You</i> , crying at a gut-wrenching episode of <i>The Last of Us</i> , and checking out the vibe of new social-networking platforms such as Bluesky and Threads.<br><br> First, here are three Sunday reads from <i>The Atlantic</i> :<br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2023/07/old-age-personality-brain-changes-psychology/674668/">The curious personality changes of older age</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/the-terrible-downside-of-ai-language-translation/674687/">Learn a foreign language before it&#39;s too late.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/heat-dome-southwest-arizona/674689/">When will the Southwest become unlivable?</a></li> <strong>The Culture Survey: Alan Taylor</strong><br><br> <b>The best novel I&#39;ve recently read:</b> I was late to discover these, but I had the best time recently tearing through <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://tertulia.com/book/the-murderbot-diaries-all-systems-red-artificial-condition-rogue-protocol-exit-strategy-martha-wells/9781250784278?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>The Murderbot Diaries</i></a> series, by Martha Wells. The adventures of Murderbot sucked me in, and each of the books was better than the one before.<br><br> <b>A quiet song that I love, and a loud song that I love:</b> Quiet song: <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q5oawMWi_L8">“Sun Will Set,” by Zoë Keating</a> . This song is so wonderful—somehow both haunting and uplifting. It&#39;s the smell of a warm campfire on a cool autumn night.<br><br> Loud song: <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lh_wesEZtKM">“Conduit,” by Russian Circles</a> . It&#39;s pure drive, a powerful series of chugging guitar riffs, bass, and drums that I would just love to hear live.<br><br> <b>The television show I&#39;m most enjoying right now:</b> Season 1 is over now, but I&#39;ve really been enjoying <i>Silo</i> on Apple TV+. I read the books a couple of years ago and remember liking them a lot, but I&#39;ve forgotten a lot of the details. The series really retains the overall feel, and the performances are great. Rebecca Ferguson, Common, and Tim Robbins really stand out.<br><br> Separately, I hope someone picks up<a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.adultswim.com/videos/joe-pera-talks-with-you"><i>Joe Pera Talks with You</i></a> , which was canceled after three seasons—it&#39;s uniquely wholesome, inviting, funny, and sometimes moving. <b>[Related:</b> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2018/12/25-best-television-episodes-2018/577996/"><b>The 25 best television episodes of 2018</b></a> <b>]</b><br><br> <b>My favorite blockbuster and favorite art movie:</b> I&#39;m going to go with my simplest answers here. Favorite blockbuster: <i>Star Wars</i> . It was the original blockbuster. I watched the first film multiple times in the theater when I was 9 years old, and it transported me in a way I never knew was possible.<br><br> Favorite art movie: I don&#39;t know if it qualifies as an “art film,” exactly, but my favorite film that is filled with quiet beauty and awe is <i>Never Cry Wolf</i> , from 1983. There are so many great moments, such as the main character, Tyler, playing his bassoon to call the wolves in, or the depth of solitude implied by the fading image of a small plane as it flies away, leaving Tyler standing alone in the middle of a frozen lake in the remote Canadian Arctic wilderness.<br><br> <b>A musical artist who means a lot to me:</b> A few years ago, when I thought that the days of hearing new heavy rock music were waning, I discovered the band Pelican and dove into its catalog, feeling the joy of rediscovering a genre. Songs such as <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RQtzU1Cxc6g">“Deny the Absolute”</a> have powered me through so many days in recent years.<br><br> <b>The last piece of entertainment that made me cry:</b> I&#39;m a total softie these days, and I get teary-eyed at the drop of a hat. That said, the most recent show that had me struggling to keep from ugly-crying was <i>The Last of Us</i> , specifically the third episode, “Long, Long Time.” I love the video game as well and have played it through several times, but that really has no bearing on the power of that episode, and the incredible story and performances by Nick Offerman and Murray Bartlett. It gets me choked up even writing about it. <b>[Related:</b> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/01/the-last-of-us-hbo-tv-series-review/672690/"><b><i>The Last of Us</i> makes the apocalypse feel new again</b> .</a> <b>]</b><br><br> <b>Something delightful introduced to me by a kid in my life:</b> Our kids started watching <i>Avatar: The Last Airbender</i> a few years ago <i>.</i> My wife and I joined them and were soon wrapped up in the whole series—amazing storytelling, great characters (Uncle Iroh is simply the best).<br><br> <b>An online creator who I&#39;m a fan of:</b> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.youtube.com/@ItchyBoots">“Itchy Boots,” also known as Noraly</a> , rides her motorcycle around the world, traveling solo and skillfully making videos documenting almost everything, including mundane border crossings and soaring panoramic drone shots. She gives a ground-level view of life and landscapes in so many places, offers interesting background information, seeks out local stories and experiences, and has an overall good and cheerful attitude that helps her navigate sometimes-difficult circumstances.<br><br> <b>A line of poetry or prose that I return to:</b> The last paragraph of Cormac McCarthy&#39;s <i>The Road</i> . I&#39;ve turned it over in my head many times. The words and phrasing are so evocative; it&#39;s a delight to read to myself, or to read aloud, and such a great exercise of concision, of summing up the impact of the entire novel that preceded it.<br><br> “Once there were brook trout in the streams in the mountains. You could see them standing in the amber current where the white edges of their fins wimpled softly in the flow. They smelled of moss in your hand. Polished and muscular and torsional. On their backs were vermiculate patterns that were maps of the world in its becoming. Maps and mazes. Of a thing which could not be put back. Not be made right again. In the deep glens where they lived all things were older than man and they hummed of mystery.” <b>[Related:</b> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/06/cormac-mccarthy-author-death-blood-meridian-passenger/674398/"><b>On the death of Cormac McCarthy</b></a> <b>]</b><br><br> <b>My favorite way of wasting time on my phone:</b> There&#39;s this game called <i>Holedown</i> , where you just aim balls to break blocks. It is the most mindless, drop-dead-simple game, and I have spent an embarrassingly large amount of time playing it. Another favorite lately: I&#39;ve been jumping from Twitter to Bluesky to Threads, figuring out the vibe of the new places and finding myself fascinated by the differences between the communities and by how people present themselves on each platform.<br><br> <b>A painting, sculpture, or other piece of visual art that I cherish:</b> I used to play the video game <i>Dishonored</i> a lot. I absolutely loved the overall visual aesthetic: the characters, the city streets, the artwork on the walls. There was a painting in a room in one of the levels that I thought was pretty great, and on a whim, I asked my wife, Chris (who was in the midst of an oil-painting phase), if she could replicate it. She did a fantastic job! It hangs in my office now, and I do indeed cherish it.<br><br> <strong>The Week Ahead</strong><br><br><li> Both<b> </b><a href="https://www.barbie-themovie.com/"><i>Barbie</i></a> and <a href="https://www.oppenheimermovie.com/"><i>Oppenheimer</i></a> debut in a box-office battle on Friday.</li><li> The fifth season of <a href="https://www.peacocktv.com/stream-tv/love-island?cid=2306orglvisldpkpdsearch13133&amp;utm_campaign=2306orglvisld&amp;utm_source=pk_ggl_gglsa&amp;utm_medium=pd_search_nonbr_srcpy&amp;utm_term=144399_d62104d&amp;utm_content=144399_d62104d_144399_d62104d&amp;gclid=CjwKCAjw-7OlBhB8EiwAnoOEkxzejJizU3CqRhmb8PuLw5FGBRE85GbIh2-rg0AjLdHW3Sg_swrJcxoCnMgQAvD_BwE&amp;gclsrc=aw.ds"><i>Love Island USA</i></a> , where participants search for love in a tropical villa as viewers vote from home on their fate (premieres on Peacock Tuesday)</li><li> <a href="https://tertulia.com/book/crook-manifesto-colson-whitehead/9780385545150?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>Crook Manifesto</i></a> , the two-time Pulitzer winner Colson Whitehead&#39;s sequel to <a href="https://tertulia.com/book/harlem-shuffle-colson-whitehead/9780525567271?affiliate_id=atl-347"><i>Harlem Shuffle</i></a> (on sale Tuesday)</li> <strong>Essay</strong><br><br> The Greatest Museum You&#39;ve Never Heard Of<br><br> <em>By Cullen Murphy</em><br><br><p> In the basement of the Biblioteca Ambrosiana, in Milan, a conservator named Vito Milo had just applied a small gel strip to the edge of a 500-year-old drawing in order to dissolve the glue that joined it to a larger paper frame. Now, with a scalpel, he worked loose a few millimeters of the drawing. I asked Milo what was in the gel, and after he rattled off a list of ingredients in Italian, I offered a layman&#39;s rough translation: “special sauce.” He smiled and nodded. “ <i>Si</i> , special sauce.”</p><p> The drawing was a page from Leonardo da Vinci&#39;s <i>Codex Atlanticus</i> , and I had been invited to witness the painstaking process of its conservation. One morning last winter, I descended to the conservators&#39; laboratory, which occupies a room just outside the steel-and-glass doorway to the Ambrosiana&#39;s gleaming vault. At the bottom of the stairs, I was stopped by an attendant, who took a coffee cup from my hands and placed it out of harm&#39;s way.</p> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/biblioteca-ambrosiana-milan-art-da-vinci-drawings/674625/">阅读全文。</a><br><br> <strong>More in Culture</strong><br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/joy-ride-bottoms-raunchy-comedies/674691/">More comedies with wild sex scenes, please.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/speak-now-better-than-revenge-taylor-swift-album-rerecording/674671/">Justice for the teenage Taylor Swift</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/insidious-the-red-door-2023-movie-review/674678/">A PG-13 horror franchise with the legs to last</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/books/archive/2023/07/bts-book-beyond-the-story-memoir/674657/">How BTS did it</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/shakespeare-in-love-movie-creativity-modernity/674632/">The everyday genius of <i>Shakespeare in Love</i></a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/culture/archive/2023/07/the-league-negro-leagues-review/674670/">How the Negro leagues shaped modern baseball</a></li> <strong>Catch Up on <em>The Atlantic</em></strong><br><br><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/heat-climate-crises-natural-disasters/674700/">Climate change feels more real now than ever.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/threads-sign-up-fomo/674696/">FOMO has never been worse on the internet.</a></li><li> <a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2023/07/covid-lab-leak-congress-investigation/674690/">The Republican lab-leak circus makes one important point.</a></li><li><a href="https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2023/07/national-debt-fiscal-trajectory/674665/">It turns out that the debt matters after all.</a></li> <strong>Photo Album</strong><br><br> A fossilized plesiosaur in New York City, Kupala Night celebrations in Ukraine, and more in our editor&#39;s selection of the week&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/photo/2023/07/photos-week-fire-bull-lava-flow-ice-cave/674698/">best photos</a> .<br><br> <i data-stringify-type="italic">Katherine Hu为本期通讯做出了贡献。</i><br><br> <em><a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://link.theatlantic.com/click/29767897.0/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudGhlYXRsYW50aWMuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLz91dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249YXRsYW50aWMtZGFpbHktbmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fY29udGVudD0yMDIyMTEyMQ/61813432e16c7128e42f4628B52865c35">Explore all of our newsletters.</a></em><br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 16 Jul 2023 11:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/joe-pera-tv-recommendations/674718/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/newsletters/archive/2023/07/joe-pera-tv-recommendations/674718/ </item><item><title><![CDATA[Delivery Apps Just Did the Impossible]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Silicon Valley is beating Domino&#39;s at its own game. <br><figure><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/AGu-O9jBTio589Oh61_Rq-CVEfE=/0x0:5337x3002/960x540/media/img/mt/2023/07/GettyImages_492047870/original.jpg" alt="A delivery vehicle with a Domino's logo on top" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Daniel Acker / Bloomberg / Getty</figcaption></figure> In recent years, Domino&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciakelso/2018/04/30/delivery-digital-provide-dominos-with-game-changing-advantages/">has</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciakelso/2018/04/30/delivery-digital-provide-dominos-with-game-changing-advantages/">sometimes</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/aliciakelso/2018/04/30/delivery-digital-provide-dominos-with-game-changing-advantages/">fancied itself</a> as a tech company with a side hustle delivering pizza. It&#39;s true. By tinkering with technology such as AI, GPS, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2019/06/17/dominos-will-start-delivering-pizzas-via-an-autonomous-robot-this-fall/">autonomous vehicles</a> , and augmented reality, the world&#39;s largest pizza chain has turned the dark art of food delivery into a science. It all started with its fabled Pizza Tracker, which launched in 2008 and created an early standard for tracking food delivery. Domino&#39;s now has something like <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://digiday.com/marketing/dominos-house-technology-push-helped-increase-online-orders/">15 different</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://digiday.com/marketing/dominos-house-technology-push-helped-increase-online-orders/">ways</a> to order a pizza, including voice assistants, Facebook Messenger, Slack, and a <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://time.com/4283913/dominos-zero-click-ordering-app/">“zero click” app</a> that automatically orders for you after 10 seconds.<br><br> All of this tech helped Domino&#39;s increase sales and streamline its operations, allowing it to finally <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.cnbc.com/2020/11/25/why-pizza-hut-is-struggling-to-against-dominos-and-papa-johns.html">“outpizza the Hut”</a> and become the facilitator of <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ir.dominos.com/news-releases/news-release-details/dominos-pizzar-announces-third-quarter-2022-financial-results">about a</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://ir.dominos.com/news-releases/news-release-details/dominos-pizzar-announces-third-quarter-2022-financial-results">third</a> of all pizza deliveries in the United States. Whereas other restaurants, pizza or otherwise, have become reliant on a constellation of third-party apps, Domino&#39;s keeps everything in-house, which means it comes out ahead—and theoretically, so do you. No Postmates, no problem: For <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.dominos.com/en/pages/order/#!/checkout/">$9.99 or so</a> —plus a small fee and a tip—a Domino&#39;s pizza driven by a Domino&#39;s driver might show up at your doorstep within 30 minutes.<br><br> But earlier this week, Domino&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dominos-pizza-strikes-deal-with-uber-in-search-for-new-sales-4e6b21fd">announced</a> that it, too, would partner with a delivery app. By the end of 2023, the hangry masses will be able to place orders for Domino&#39;s pies and various sodium bombs through Uber Eats in most places (though Domino&#39;s drivers will still deliver the food). By joining forces with Uber, the company is acknowledging how dominant delivery apps such as DoorDash, Uber Eats, and Grubhub have become—using them is approaching a necessary requirement for restaurants to stay afloat. If Domino&#39;s can&#39;t stay off the delivery apps, can anyone?<br><br> Fittingly enough, the American food-delivery craze actually began with Domino&#39;s. The company <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.nytimes.com/1986/09/27/business/pizza-s-home-delivery-war.html">is often credited</a> with popularizing the concept of pizza delivery ( <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/01/pizza-delivery-box-design-soggy/672712/">it</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/01/pizza-delivery-box-design-soggy/672712/">created the modern-day pizza box</a> , and co-founder Tom Monaghan even <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2007/02/19/the-deliverer">met his wife</a> while delivering a pizza). The delivery-centric Domino&#39;s model managed remarkable longevity, even as pizza ordering went from landlines and cellphones to dial-up to mobile apps. In 2011, not long after then-CEO Patrick Doyle embarked on <a data-event-element="inline link" href="http://pizzaturnaround.com/">an unlikely national ad campaign</a> conceding that his pizza kinda sucks, he <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.ncr.com/blogs/restaurants/digital-innovations-dominos">issued a challenge</a> to his technology team: He wanted ordering a pizza to be easy enough that someone could do it while waiting at a stoplight. Mobile ordering was the future, and in the future, pizza orders should take only 17 seconds.<br><br> In a sense, Domino&#39;s has become a victim of its own success. The company&#39;s technological savvy helped prime the public for more than just pizza delivery. These third-party apps appeared during the gig-economy boom of the 2010s and then exploded during the early pandemic. Food-delivery sales could have gone the way of Peloton as the pandemic slowed, but <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www2.deloitte.com/us/en/pages/consumer-business/articles/future-of-restaurants-study.html">they haven&#39;t</a> . Roughly 14 percent of pizza sales <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dominos-pizza-strikes-deal-with-uber-in-search-for-new-sales-4e6b21fd">took place</a> through delivery apps in the past year, alongside an array of dishes and cuisines that would make a diner menu look meek. As of 2023, hundreds of thousands of restaurants are on delivery apps, offering dry-aged steaks from fine-dining spots and <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mcdonalds.com/us/en-us/product/steak-egg-cheese-bagel.html">dry steak bagel</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.mcdonalds.com/us/en-us/product/steak-egg-cheese-bagel.html">s</a> from McDonald&#39;s. Restaurant dining rooms may be full again, but the apps <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://secondmeasure.com/datapoints/food-delivery-services-grubhub-uber-eats-doordash-postmates/">are now pulling in more revenue</a> than ever before.<br><br> In other words, they&#39;ve simply gotten too big to ignore. Even though Domino&#39;s will continue to deliver its own pizzas, its CEO, Russell Weiner, <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.restaurantbusinessonline.com/financing/dominos-uber-eats-deal-acknowledges-reality-third-party-marketplace">has put the cost of missing out</a> in plain terms when discussing the Uber Eats deal: “There&#39;s $5 billion of pizza sales happening on the aggregator platforms … [that] we should have a third of.”<br><br> With millions of restaurant workers preparing orders and millions of gig workers delivering for them, an entire food-delivery ecosystem has coalesced, which has enormous implications for both restaurants and dining culture as a whole. These apps can charge restaurants fees that <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/clark-county/clark-county-caps-third-party-food-delivery-fees-at-15-2087939/">stretch up to</a> <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.reviewjournal.com/news/politics-and-government/clark-county/clark-county-caps-third-party-food-delivery-fees-at-15-2087939/">30 percent</a> , imposing a burden that requires wild order volume to break even in a business that already has tight margins. They have so much power that they are now influencing the <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://get.grubhub.com/blog/delivery-menu-tips/">menus of restaurants</a> , sometimes even if you dine in. The delivery workers making all of this function, meanwhile, are still paid low wages as independent contractors with no protections or bargaining power.<br><br> For diners, bringing tech even further into the restaurant industry has costs. According to a 2021 report, food-delivery apps <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.pcmag.com/how-to/social-media-and-food-delivery-apps-sell-the-most-personal-data">stand alongside</a> the social-media giants as the biggest collectors and peddlers of consumer personal data. By Domino&#39;s <a data-event-element="inline link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dominos-pizza-strikes-deal-with-uber-in-search-for-new-sales-4e6b21fd">own admission</a> , Uber&#39;s willingness to hand over customer data was a key factor in its decision to strike up a deal with the company. Even as it becomes easier and more convenient to order anything to your couch, delivery apps will continue to force restaurants to bend their operations to suit them. That matters whether you order delivery every night or have never used an app at all.<br><br></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 15 Jul 2023 12:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/dominos-deliver-uber-eats-app/674716/</guid><link/> https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2023/07/dominos-deliver-uber-eats-app/674716/</item></channel></rss>